<subSubSection id="C308EFA4810AD107072D5F1CF9D3F98D" pageId="9" pageNumber="191" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BADBC2F810AD107072D5F1CF9D3F98D" blockId="9.[259,1092,1148,1652]" pageId="9" pageNumber="191">
<emphasis id="B966603D810AD107072D5F1CFBAEFAB2" bold="true" box="[285,409,1334,1355]" pageId="9" pageNumber="191">Discussion.</emphasis>
This is the only species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C12C7AC810AD10704E05F1DF90CFAB5" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[720,827,1335,1356]" family="Bruchidae" pageId="9" pageNumber="201" rank="family">Bruchidae</taxonomicName>
that we know in which males (or females) have two strong spines on the basal portion of the metasternum. The male genitalia are very different from other species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C12C7AC810AD10705FA5F47FE75FA7B" box="[970,1090,1389,1410]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Meibomeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B966603D810AD10705FA5F47FE75FA7B" box="[970,1090,1389,1410]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="191">Meibomeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="1329A0AA810AD107073A5FADFB41FA65" box="[266,374,1415,1436]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="10.[279,322,1302,1321]" captionTargetBox="[255,1090,272,1274]" captionTargetId="figure-12@10.[247,1095,265,1281]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs. 8–9. Meibomeus juarez male genitalia. 8) Median lobe; 9) lateral lobes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4900437" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4900437/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="191">Figs. 8, 9</figureCitation>
). The basal metasternal spines and structure of the male genitalia are differentiating external and internal features of this species and leave no doubt that this is a distinct species. 
<taxonomicName id="4C12C7AC810AD10704B35F97F972FA2B" box="[643,837,1469,1490]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Meibomeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juarez">
<emphasis id="B966603D810AD10704B35F97F972FA2B" box="[643,837,1469,1490]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="191">Meibomeus juarez</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares the pecten without a large tooth and with four to five small teeth on the hind femur (
<figureCitation id="1329A0AA810AD10705CA5FF2FE0CFA14" box="[1018,1083,1496,1517]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[282,316,856,875]" captionText="Fig. 7. Meibomeus juarez hind leg." pageId="9" pageNumber="191">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) with 
<taxonomicName id="4C12C7AC810AD107070B5FD9F802F9F1" authority="(Sharp)" baseAuthorityName="Sharp" box="[315,565,1523,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Meibomeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serraticulus">
<emphasis id="B966603D810AD107070B5FD9FBE9F9F1" box="[315,478,1523,1544]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="191">M. serraticulus</emphasis>
(Sharp)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C12C7AC810AD107045F5FD9F903F9F1" authority="(Sharp)" baseAuthorityName="Sharp" box="[623,820,1523,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Meibomeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viduus">
<emphasis id="B966603D810AD107045F5FD9F8EFF9F1" box="[623,728,1523,1544]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="191">M. viduus</emphasis>
(Sharp)
</taxonomicName>
. The integument color is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C12C7AC810AD107075D5C24F93EF9DA" authority="Kingsolver and Whitehead" authorityName="Kingsolver and Whitehead" box="[365,777,1550,1571]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Meibomeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hidalgoi">
<emphasis id="B966603D810AD107075D5C24FBD0F9DA" box="[365,487,1550,1571]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="191">M. hidalgoi</emphasis>
Kingsolver and Whitehead
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<taxonomicName id="4C12C7AC810AD107050B5C24F9A8F9DA" box="[827,927,1550,1571]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Meibomeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juarez">
<emphasis id="B966603D810AD107050B5C24F9A8F9DA" box="[827,927,1550,1571]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="191">M. juarez</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs because its first abdominal sternum does not have a polished lateral apical band. 
<taxonomicName id="4C12C7AC810AD10702165C03FB73F9A0" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Meibomeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juarez">
<emphasis id="B966603D810AD10702165C03FB73F9A0" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="191">M. juarez</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a robust body shape as does the 
<typeStatus id="54A9028D810AD10704FC5C6EF910F9A0" box="[716,807,1604,1625]" pageId="9" pageNumber="191">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C12C7AC810AD107057C5C6EFB95F98D" authority="Kingsolver and Whitehead" authorityName="Kingsolver and Whitehead" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Meibomeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="howdeni">
<emphasis id="B966603D810AD107057C5C6EF9FFF9A0" box="[844,968,1604,1625]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="191">M. howdeni</emphasis>
Kingsolver and Whitehead
</taxonomicName>
but the latter does not have basal metasternal spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
